Thinking about how cake was invented in Antiquity as an instrument towards pure hedonism, trying to reap pleasurable sensation outside the natural limit. It takes a certain brutality to truly appreciate cake as a substance, like the one maldisciplined children or psychopaths have

One can imagine The Judge from Cormac McCarthy's novel truly delighting in a cake. "Portal" Valve vidya features a joke where a cake recipe turns into mortuary instructions on how to preserve, prepare a human body, but there is something of the cannibalistic in real cake-making.

An old cave church I visited last year held an inscription like "Blessed is the man who build a granary" and I contemplated how grain storehouses prevent starvation and cannibalism, like Joseph's Egypt granaries in the Old Testament, but a cake is a "reimagination" of man-eating.

The Hagakure saying that if a man is unable to find a good living model to imitate, he should "make" a model himself by choosing a point from many persons each, e.g. one's politeness, another's bravery, etc., reminds me of Auguste Rodin's method of combining sculptural fragments.

"One for the proper way of speaking, one for correct conduct and one for steadiness of mind. Thus will the model be made. If one perceives a person’s good points, he will have a model for anything."
